<p><b>Norm on Mon, 4th Jun 2012 8:36 am&nbsp;</b></p>
<div style="float:left;margin:3px 20px 10px 0px;"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/6f85e02a8b230e80d3895078c7751c51?s=96&amp;d=&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-96 photo' height='96' width='96'/></div>
<p>Dont wanna discourage somebody&#8217;s creative writing, nor discourage their project car. However, recycling does not mean that you are forced to throw the copper in with the steel, and spending a couple of man years and a hundred pounds of lithium batteries to save a car just might NOT be very environmetnally friendly. If the car were correctly recycled (without the apathetic lack of detail) the copper would be pulled out first, and other metals too. This is called &#8216;de-manufacturing&#8217;, something that basically nobody does. Its hard to &#8216;turn the sows ear into a silk purse&#8217; I find it hard to believe that taking old junk and rebuilding it is going to be the right solution, however a more vigorous amount of de-manufacturing would get the right metals to the right smelters and then you get the shiny new car (without the open-pit mining and without taking a year of your life to rebuild old rusty junk). De-manufacturing is labor intensive (I do some of it myself in a corner of the garage, sometimes finding that a brass nugget can be pulled loose from a piece of steel, and so on). I am impressed that absolutely nobody is willing to do it, even though its satisfying, especially the &#8216;greener than thou&#8217; eco-liberals who will gladly burn up 50 gallons of gas to &#8216;get to the conference&#8217; but would never in a million years pull pieces of copper wire loose from an old water tank. Those activities are left to scrappers, or just nobody does it at all. Then the author is triumphant in his claim that the copper &amp; aluminum gets melted into the next batch of steel etc. even though that fundamental premise of this article, need not be the case.</p>
