<li class="alt" id="comment-24639">
<p><b>Kenz300 on Mon, 4th Jun 2012 1:29 pm&nbsp;</b></p>
<div style="float:left;margin:3px 20px 10px 0px;"><img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/b185ed68760007abf9023767e2b593b7?s=96&amp;d=&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-96 photo' height='96' width='96'/></div>
<p>Biofuels can now be made from trash or waste. Every landfill can be converted to produce biofuels, energy (methane) and recycled raw materials for new products. This is a much more sustainable solution to our discarded materials. Reduce, reuse and recycle was once part of an effort to deal with material shortages in the war effort. Our grandparents were much less wasteful than the current generation. In the future we may have little choice but to be less wasteful.</p>
</div>
<div style="margin-bottom:20px; padding:0px 0px 0px 0px; clear:both;"></div>
</li>
<div class="commentleft">
<li class="alt" id="comment-24641">
<p><b>BillT on Mon, 4th Jun 2012 3:21 pm&nbsp;</b></p>
<div style="float:left;margin:3px 20px 10px 0px;"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/cbf39c6cd008869d8dfcc504383d4d67?s=96&amp;d=&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-96 photo' height='96' width='96'/></div>
<p>Kenz, even the landfill pictured above would not pay back the coast of building a plant to make biofuels. It would all be gone in the first year of operation. Not to mention that there is all kinds of unwanted trash like toxins, lead, etc in that trash. If it doesn&#8217;t produce a profit, it will not be done.</p>
